[
    {
        "index": 1,
        "start_time": 8245,
        "end_time": 13226,
        "text": "Is it a flying comma,\nor a quotation mark chopped in half?"
    },
    {
        "index": 2,
        "start_time": 13226,
        "end_time": 17885,
        "text": "Either way, you may already be well-versed\nin how to use the apostrophe,"
    },
    {
        "index": 3,
        "start_time": 17885,
        "end_time": 20705,
        "text": "but here&#39;s a quick refresher on its usage."
    },
    {
        "index": 4,
        "start_time": 20705,
        "end_time": 23792,
        "text": "The apostrophe can be used in three ways:"
    },
    {
        "index": 5,
        "start_time": 23792,
        "end_time": 25550,
        "text": "to mark possession,"
    },
    {
        "index": 6,
        "start_time": 25550,
        "end_time": 27965,
        "text": "to mark contraction,"
    },
    {
        "index": 7,
        "start_time": 27965,
        "end_time": 31173,
        "text": "to mark the plural of single letters."
    },
    {
        "index": 8,
        "start_time": 31173,
        "end_time": 35292,
        "text": "Most of the time, if you see an apostrophe\nhovering helpfully near a word,"
    },
    {
        "index": 9,
        "start_time": 35292,
        "end_time": 38605,
        "text": "it&#39;s trying to mark possession \nor contraction."
    },
    {
        "index": 10,
        "start_time": 38605,
        "end_time": 42552,
        "text": "First, let&#39;s look at how the apostrophe\nmarks possession."
    },
    {
        "index": 11,
        "start_time": 42552,
        "end_time": 45666,
        "text": "As you can see, the placement\nof this punctuation mark"
    },
    {
        "index": 12,
        "start_time": 45666,
        "end_time": 49298,
        "text": "can really change \nthe meaning of a sentence."
    },
    {
        "index": 13,
        "start_time": 49298,
        "end_time": 52768,
        "text": "&quot;Those robots in \nthe sand are my sister&#39;s.&quot;"
    },
    {
        "index": 14,
        "start_time": 52768,
        "end_time": 56596,
        "text": "&quot;Those robots in \nthe sand are my sisters.&#39;&quot;"
    },
    {
        "index": 15,
        "start_time": 56596,
        "end_time": 60799,
        "text": "&quot;Those robots in the sand are my sisters.&quot;"
    },
    {
        "index": 16,
        "start_time": 60799,
        "end_time": 64586,
        "text": "When showing possession, the apostrophe\nbelongs next to the noun"
    },
    {
        "index": 17,
        "start_time": 64586,
        "end_time": 67028,
        "text": "that owns or possesses something."
    },
    {
        "index": 18,
        "start_time": 67028,
        "end_time": 69986,
        "text": "The noun can be singular or plural."
    },
    {
        "index": 19,
        "start_time": 69986,
        "end_time": 72172,
        "text": "Proper nouns work, too."
    },
    {
        "index": 20,
        "start_time": 72172,
        "end_time": 76230,
        "text": "So if Lucy needs to get her robots\nunder control before they cause mayhem,"
    },
    {
        "index": 21,
        "start_time": 76230,
        "end_time": 80355,
        "text": "those dangerous creatures \nwould be &quot;Lucy&#39;s robots.&quot;"
    },
    {
        "index": 22,
        "start_time": 80355,
        "end_time": 82451,
        "text": "But what if Lucy was Lucas?"
    },
    {
        "index": 23,
        "start_time": 82451,
        "end_time": 86788,
        "text": "Would we write &quot;Lucas&#39; robots&quot;\nor &quot;Lucas&#39;s robots&quot;?"
    },
    {
        "index": 24,
        "start_time": 86788,
        "end_time": 90744,
        "text": "And what if Lucas gave his robots\nto the Robinsons family?"
    },
    {
        "index": 25,
        "start_time": 90744,
        "end_time": 95425,
        "text": "Would it be &quot;The Robinsons&#39; robots,&quot;\nor &quot;The Robinsons&#39;s robots&quot;?"
    },
    {
        "index": 26,
        "start_time": 95425,
        "end_time": 100117,
        "text": "The truth is, even grammar nerds\ndisagree on the right thing to do."
    },
    {
        "index": 27,
        "start_time": 100117,
        "end_time": 106062,
        "text": "The use of &#39;s after a proper noun\nending in s is a style issue,"
    },
    {
        "index": 28,
        "start_time": 106062,
        "end_time": 108540,
        "text": "not a hard and fast grammar rule."
    },
    {
        "index": 29,
        "start_time": 108540,
        "end_time": 111015,
        "text": "It&#39;s a conundrum \nwithout a simple answer."
    },
    {
        "index": 30,
        "start_time": 111015,
        "end_time": 114640,
        "text": "Professional writers solve this problem\nby learning what&#39;s considered correct"
    },
    {
        "index": 31,
        "start_time": 114640,
        "end_time": 117401,
        "text": "for a publication, and doing that."
    },
    {
        "index": 32,
        "start_time": 117401,
        "end_time": 119690,
        "text": "The important thing is to pick one style"
    },
    {
        "index": 33,
        "start_time": 119690,
        "end_time": 123311,
        "text": "and stick with it \nthroughout a piece of writing."
    },
    {
        "index": 34,
        "start_time": 123311,
        "end_time": 124219,
        "text": "One more wrinkle."
    },
    {
        "index": 35,
        "start_time": 124219,
        "end_time": 127938,
        "text": "Certain pronouns already \nhave possession built in"
    },
    {
        "index": 36,
        "start_time": 127938,
        "end_time": 130132,
        "text": "and don&#39;t need an apostrophe."
    },
    {
        "index": 37,
        "start_time": 130132,
        "end_time": 134780,
        "text": "Remembering that will help you avoid one\nof the trickiest snags in English grammar:"
    },
    {
        "index": 38,
        "start_time": 134780,
        "end_time": 137087,
        "text": "its vs. it&#39;s."
    },
    {
        "index": 39,
        "start_time": 137087,
        "end_time": 142940,
        "text": "&quot;It&#39;s&quot; only take an apostrophe when it&#39;s\na contraction for &quot;it is&quot; or &quot;it has.&quot;"
    },
    {
        "index": 40,
        "start_time": 142940,
        "end_time": 145835,
        "text": "If you can replace &quot;it&#39;s&quot; with \none of those two phrases,"
    },
    {
        "index": 41,
        "start_time": 145835,
        "end_time": 147946,
        "text": "use the apostrophe."
    },
    {
        "index": 42,
        "start_time": 147946,
        "end_time": 150619,
        "text": "If you&#39;re showing possession, \nleave it out."
    },
    {
        "index": 43,
        "start_time": 150619,
        "end_time": 153960,
        "text": "Otherwise, contractions \nare pretty straightforward."
    },
    {
        "index": 44,
        "start_time": 153960,
        "end_time": 156588,
        "text": "The apostrophe stands in \nfor missing letters,"
    },
    {
        "index": 45,
        "start_time": 156588,
        "end_time": 160418,
        "text": "and lets common phrases \nsquash into a single word."
    },
    {
        "index": 46,
        "start_time": 160418,
        "end_time": 163336,
        "text": "In rare cases, you can have \na double contraction,"
    },
    {
        "index": 47,
        "start_time": 163336,
        "end_time": 166354,
        "text": "though those generally \naren&#39;t accepted in writing,"
    },
    {
        "index": 48,
        "start_time": 166354,
        "end_time": 168853,
        "text": "with the exception of dialogue."
    },
    {
        "index": 49,
        "start_time": 168853,
        "end_time": 172175,
        "text": "So it&#39;s possessive, \nit&#39;s often followed by s&#39;s,"
    },
    {
        "index": 50,
        "start_time": 172175,
        "end_time": 176187,
        "text": "and it&#39;s sometimes tricky \nwhen it comes to its usage."
    },
    {
        "index": 51,
        "start_time": 176187,
        "end_time": 178203,
        "text": "It&#39;s the apostrophe."
    }
]